Would you like help turning these HTML/CSS elements into a small browser extension or note‑widget so it auto‑loads whenever you open your writing app?

Great—you can automate it in just a few minutes.  
If you write mostly in a browser, **Stylus** is the simplest route because it only needs CSS (no scripting).  
Here’s a lightweight setup that works in Chrome, Edge, and Firefox:

---

### 🧩 Steps (Stylus)

1. **Install Stylus** from your browser’s extension store.  
2. Open any page or web app where you write (for example, your note tool).  
3. Click the Stylus icon → *Manage* → *Write new style for this URL*.  
4. Paste this code:

   ```css
   @-moz-document domain("your‑notes‑site.com") {
     :root {
       --accent: seagreen;
     }
     #supportFooter {
       width: 100%;
       padding: 6px 0;
       text-align: center;
       font-family: 'Noto Sans', Calibri, Arial, sans-serif;
       font-size: 0.9rem;
       border-top: 1px solid GrayText;
       background-color: Canvas;
       color: CanvasText;
       animation: fadeIn 1s ease;
     }
     #supportFooter::before {
       content: "";
       display: block;
       height: 2px;
       background-color: var(--accent);
       margin-bottom: 4px;
     }
     #supportFooter::after {
       content: "🌿 Mirror → Reflect → Act → Normalize → Refer";
     }
     @keyframes fadeIn { from {opacity:0;} to {opacity:1;} }
     body::after { content: ""; display: block; height: 32px; } /* spacing if needed */
     body > :last-child::after {
       content: "";
     }
   }
   ```

5. Save the style and refresh the page—your footer will appear automatically at the bottom, adjusting to light or dark themes.

---

If you ever want different mottos on different domains, duplicate the style in Stylus and change only the text inside `#supportFooter::after`.

